            <h2 class="custom-header">Short Story about Sweet History</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="custom-details">
            <p>
                Wasco de Gama, the great seaman, founded the sea route to South India around 1200 AD.
                Thereby, Sri Lanka (then known as Ceylon) was also linked to the Silk Road.
                The Arabs who travelled this route introduced Arabica coffee (Coffea Arabica .L) to
                Sri Lanka.
            </p>
            <p>
                Somewhere around the year 1658, the Dutch who held the maritime regions of Sri Lanka,
                started cultivating Arabica coffee as a commercial commodity. Nearly two centuries later,
                in 1815, the British succesfully invaded and subjugated the whole island. Around this
                time, demand for coffee was growing in the European market and Sir Edward Barnes (who would
                later become Governor) started the first true coffee plantation in 1823 at Sinhapitiya, in
                Gampola. Towards the end of 1847, coffee plantations in Sri Lanka covered around 276,000 arces.
                By 1870, the coffee industry in Sri Lanka was booming. It had become the world's largest
                producer of coffee, exporting over a million hundred weights (about 50,000 mt) annually.
            </p>
            <p>
                Tragically, disaster struck the coffee industry in 1886 in the form of a fungal leaf disease
                called Leaf Rust signalling the end of an era. The world renowned Ceylon Coffee all but disappeared.
            </p>
        </div>
